Much of the building is generally Gothic, as indicated by the stellar/lierne vaults covering the nave and transepts. Additionally, we can see that it is English, as indicated the fan vault that belongs to the English "perpendicular Gothic" style, even though it comes from a later phase of construction. These two elements together demonstrate that the building is an English Gothic church.

The whole exterior looks to be of the same style and each part has Renaissance features. The ornate stone revetment and use of semi-precious stones to decorate the walls suggest its Venetian origin. Therefore Venetian Renaissance.

This building is pretty homogenous in style (Venetian Renaissance) and while it draws on a lot of classical and Byzantine forms, its use of classical proportions and forms, as well as certain details like the kind of stones used and their particular application, all indicate that it is a Venetian Renaissance building.

In addition to being a uniquely homogenous case in terms of its style, this church is also quite unique and famous so it would be likely that a style classification would be informed by simply recognizing the particular building in this case.
paintings depicting the history of the Carmelite order; these paintings line the nave and are in the Baroque style; added hundreds of years after the church's original construction
gilded and painted wooden carvings of angels and important holy figures; these were added in the late 16th-early 17th century and adorn both sides of the nave
This image shows the church's nave and apse. In this image Gothic, Renaissance, and Baroque elements are present thus making it challenging to assign the building one style.
groin vaults; probably belong to the Renaissance changes around 1500
ribbed apse; this is very gothic in style and another one of the few remaining elements that harken back to this structure's Gothic beginnings
can see evidence of where a round, potentially Gothic rose window was later filled in when this main facade was revised during the Renaissance

I know that this church is located in Venice not just from the Trilobe facade, but also because on the ground in front of the entrance it is clear that part of a canal was filled in. Note the white marble showing the outline of what used to be water.

Like the other aspects of this church, the main facade is a hybrid. While some of the original Gothic elements remain (trilobe facade), a lot of Baroque features have been added (the pediment, sculpture + niche).
trilobe facade; this shape of the facade is connected to 15th century Venice thus helping aid in the Venetian Gothic style classification

tabernacle frame; a frame around a doorway having two columns or pilasters on a base supporting a pediment; the columns appear to be classical in style; this framing of the main doorway into the church is a Baroque addition (17th century)
open pediment with rounded side pieces; pediments are a classical feature that were revisited in styles such as Renaissance and Baroque; this is a Baroque addition (17th century)
niche that houses a sculpture; includes a scallop shell decoration at the top which is commonly found in Italian niches; Baroque 17th century addition
classical column that helps support a broken pediment; probably a Renaissance edition.

broken pediment; the use of the classical element of the pediment is very common in Baroque architecture; broken pediments can be found on some Roman architecture e.g. at Petra in Jordan and it is revived in late Renaissance and very popular on baroque altars like this one
ribbed apse; this feature is clearly from the original Gothic structure; very gothic in style
colonette; these slender columns which can be seen throughout the apse are a very Gothic stylistic element
While the Gothic roots of the building shine through in this image of the apse, the style classification is muddled by later ornamental additions.
these more simple stone columns are stylistically gothic

This building is a great edge case example because it is hybrid in style. While the structure was originally constructed during the Gothic period, not many gothic features are visible. Many additions and changes have been made to the church's decoration over the years and so Renaissance and Baroque elements are also present.
